author: @nashsok
text: For anyone following along in Python 3, the zip() function works a bit differently in Python 3 than it did in Python 2, returning an zip object iterator, rather than an iterable.  In order to create a dict with a 'for' loop as shown in this tutorial you'll need to cast the zip object to a list using the list() function  for name, hero in list(zip(names, heros)):      my_dict[name] = hero  Or, to create a dict with a comprehension:  my_dict = {name: hero for name, hero in list(zip(names, heros))}

author: @nawendusingh2858
text: for those who found this channel late,Corey is using Python 2 and the map+lambda function in this example will return a map object  in Python 3.x. more explanation can be found at https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1303347/getting-a-map-to-return-a-list-in-python-3-x.  The following 2 ways now work in Python 3:- 1.  my_list = [*map(lambda n: n*n, nums)]  print(my_list) 2. my_list = map(lambda n: n*n, nums) print(list(my_list))
